,Recommended,224460,25430366,"Posted: 9 September, 2016",all,hoserama99,"I can never tell when a game will click with me. Contrast is one of those that I didn't think I'd like, but I did.The setting of the game is well-realized: art nouveau/art deco with a jazzy early 20th century theme. It was a fantastic change of pace from the usual common game themes, and it was well done here.As well, the mechanic of shifting into and out of shadow to complete platforming tasks was a neat twist on the usual platforming mechanics. I'm not a big fan of platformers (and this game didn't change my mind) but the novelty of this at least made it feel unique and somewhat fresh.The story was a nice noir concept, and it doesn't get in its own way with crazy twists - it exists and is fairly comprehensible, while suiting the game and its mechanics.As for downsides, I found the gamepad controls to be a little ""loose"" and slippery - movement felt overly-sensistive to me, and I sometimes had trouble controlling my jumps. There were a few puzzles that are not intuitive, but that's OK I suppose - the game isn't meant to be a complete cakewalk.I'd definitely recommend this if you're in the mood for something unique and noir and platform-y: 4 out of 5."
