76561198009430218,Recommended,224460,16572323,"Posted: 20 June, 2015",all,JacoRay,"Contrast succeeds at being surreal and cute at the same time. Cute only because of the secondary main character and her naivity.As a 3D platformer, it is very short, but boasts a wonderful art style that is also creepy in a Tim Burton kind of way.You play as Dawn, an 'imaginary' friend to Didi, the daughter of Kat and Vincenzo. Didi's adoptive father is actually this guy named Johnny who's trying to make a name for himself. The overall story has overtones of mafia involvement, magic, illuisions, etc. It has a very early 1900's feel to it but the world is so surreal with the city that the game takes place being on floating islands. And the clockwork systems and other stuff.The standout element is the ability to shift from the real world to the shadow world, similar to, I think it's Paper Mario where he can stick and travel on the walls. Or one of the Legend of Zelda's where Link actually does transform into a shadow of sorts. Well, it's like that. Dawn has that ability basically.I guess my only complaints would be the lack of ambient sounds and the length of the game. Otherwise, pretty good.7.5/10"
76561198031749387,Recommended,224460,16718722,"Posted: 26 June, 2015",all,silversnake7,"I'd consider ""Contrast"" one of the ""Indie gems"" of our time.It's a modern game with some fresh ideas, but also obvious roots in some classics.The whole design, the art, the music, the story, the levels, the mechanics, it all plays together very well, creating a rounded experience.The story soon became more intense than I expected, driving me forwards, wanting to know what happens next.The levels, puzzles and platform sequenses aren't very big or difficult, though sometimes there are little to no indicators what to do next, just a little exploration or trial should provide the solution.The main mechanic of using light and shadow is just amazing, used in various ways, keeping it interesting, only sometimes it seems a little rough/ glitchy.The only ""negative"" i could say about the whole game is that i would've wished for some more of it all, a little bit more story, a little bit more gameplay to go through, (even) more things that could've been done with the mechanics and a bit more smoothing out the little edges of the game. So i would wish for a bigger, second part, or a spinoff or something, but that's not even really a bad thing to say about ""Contrast"" itself."
76561198068919027,Recommended,224460,7892793,"Posted: 3 December, 2013",all,dana13424,"Contrast is short, has a few minor bugs and flaws. There was actually a lot that erked me. For example, the game screwed with my mouse sensitivity in game, so i had to tweak it so the camera wasn't making me dizzy. Also, it was a bit more demanding on my pc then i thought it would (but my pc is old. Any up to date pc should do fine). Fixed camera angles when interecting with objects can also be a bit obnoxious.However... for the flaws, this game was really enjoyable. It's a bit of soul food, makes you think and ask questions. It feels substantial as far as the story and the world is concerned (Some say gameplay is lacking challange, but for me it lacked a lot of the frustration that can come with some puzzle games with obtuse solutions. For example, the secret star solutions in Braid, one of which requires you to do nothing but wait for nearly 40 minutes or so). The art is fantastic, definitely different from what i've played recently. The Music and overal sound design is wonderful, though the voice acting isn't the best.Contrast is one of those examples of ""Games are Art"" while still being a game, as opposed to a tour with some narration over top. If you don't mind a short, but fufilling experiance or some so so gameplay, and you want a great story, world, and overall aesthetic then pick up contrast. If you want something challanging, lengthy, and a bit shallower (i.e. good dumb fun such as Painkiller) then look elsewhere. A game for when you're in the mood, and a damn good one if you end up playing it in that mood."
,Recommended,224460,16481791,"Posted: 17 June, 2015",all,Vi,"TLDR: Interesting game with interesting ideas, smooth gameplay and a lovely story-presentation. Unfortunately too short and expensive (when not on sale) considering the amount of content it offers, but still worth a try.Full review:A short (REALLY short, finished it with 100% of the achievements in under 3 hours) platforming game which in a way reminds me of the Portal games since, as one of the game's achievements references to by name, rather than thinking with portals here you are ""Thinking with Shadows"". Can't reach your objective in the 3d perspective environment? time to start looking for a way to make the shadow of objects, buildings or ""people"" (even tho they are invisible to your eyes) help you, so that you can then shift into the walls and do 2d perspective platforming with the shadows. The fluidity in which you do this change between the 3d world and the 2d shadows is very smooth. Yes you will run into a few ""buggy"" spots but they are few and don't really break the gameplay.Story-wise, it is a charm. You could consider it 2 stories, one of the young girl Didi's desire to be with her parents and to make them be happy, which is the focus point for most of the game's lenght, and a more subtle one which springs up near the end related to Dawn, the character you control, about who exactly is she and why she has the powers she has. Mind you, its not the best story ever but it works well for the game and the way it is presented is pretty good.Again, short game and expensive considering the amount of playtime it can offer (I'd recommend buying it when it is on sale with a 60-ish or more % discount) but what little you get is in my opinion quality content worth checking out. Hopefully we see a similar premise, or maybe even a proper game sequel, in the future from this developer."
