,Recommended,224460,23576506,"Posted: 15 June, 2016",all,Mountaineer,fun indie game with puzzles and a small story.
,Recommended,224460,12515555,"Posted: 16 October, 2014",all,Taleweaver,"Damn two way system...this would've been neither a thumbs up nor a thumbs down but a middle ground. It has some strong points, as well as some lesser ones. I'll see if I can post it without one to get around that pickle.The strong points sort of sells itself on the store: the visuals and the ideas. Oh, and the voice-acting and the audio.Theme-wise, this is a wonderful film noir kind of feel with the old stylish drama and some genuinely fitting soundtracks that perfectly fit the gameplay mechanics. Climbing the shadow of the musicians or the voice actors while they are acting their part is original to say the least. As well as having the far majority of the cast consist merely of shadows (which gives the game a strange atmosphere).Unfortunately, while the gameplay is certainly fitting with the theme, the switching between 3rd person adventuring and 2d 'shadow' platforming doesn't quite mix that well. Despite the contrast in lighting, you sometimes have to guess where you can fade in the shadows, and sometimes you almost randomly drop out again. And rearranging lights in a 3D plane is a lot harder to properly 'aim' than in a 2D one (for those who are familiar with A shadow's tale: control was much tighter there).I'm not so sure what to think of the plot. While the atmosphere, voices and visuals are all in place, I wasn't drawn into the game much. I partly blame the clunky controls and some glaring bugs (I encountered numerous invisible walls and pass-through walls), and partly because the far majority of the game you're just a nanny for Didi (""let's fix this! let's fix that!""), while your own role isn't explained until nearly the end (which is a shame. How am I supposed to care for the characters if I don't know what my own role in the play is to begin with?).While contrast also has some platforming and puzzle segments, the only real meat is the storyline. It has those things, and they sort of work, but you'll push on through to get the next cutscene. And with that in mind, it should at the very least be labeled at ""not bad at all"". Awesome would be giving it too much credit, but it's certainly decent.I just wish more was put into it. Bug testing. The conversations. Perhaps some extra thought for lip syncing (there is only one character who has all the monologues, but her lips seem to say something competely different).But all in all, I'd say this is the sort of game I would give a 6.5 - 7. It's a good game. Not a great one. All in my opinion, of course. :-)"
76561198019193223,Recommended,224460,13313493,"Posted: 10 December, 2014",all,Galadhatan,"Ok, so. This game is what I would  call a good ""sophomore effort"", in that it has some really good potentials: the character Didi is a likable enough character (though Dawn seems standoffish and unfriendly, especially for an avatar, and her raison d'etre is critically neglected), the concept of shadow-running is promising, and the set pieces are generally very good. The songs of the soundtrack, when there is any soundtrack, are very nice period pieces (1920's), much like LA Noire uses to establish atmosphere. In fact, a resemblence to LA Noire is strong from the title screen (though it ends there).  The use of shadows is very creative, and watching all of the family drama (I'm not entirely a fan of the non-existence of real people, just their shadows, though I admit it's a good concept) while they also pose the platforms you navigate is well done.Despite its promising start, it requires a considerable more polish before I'd call it great. The action and movement of Dawn, the avatar, is clumsy, sometimes failing to jump into shadows, sometimes not dashing correctly, rather often falling out of the shadow despite your best effort. This is a game requiring dexterous dual-joystick control, one for movement (which was by default absurdly inverted, and required some inner-game config editing to fix) and another for camera, and both need to move to execute the required jumps in places. The character model herself is rather unappealling, in running, turning, and standing. Like Papo y Yo (a game with a similar feel in playing), Contrast feels outdated even while you feel you should be enjoying it more. I suspect is has a lot to do with its use of the Unreal Engine, which (I can't confirm this, not knowing much about programing with the UE) seemed an unfortunately easy shortcut to making the game.  This is a game with such good story, concept, graphics, and voice-acting (for the most part, at least) that its central mechanism really unfortunately spoils it.Not to kick it while it's down, but it could really use some more polish in its foley effects and soundtrack generally, and mappable controls. Further, the puzzles are more tedious than challenging, such that, while you can enjoy the ingenuity of the shadow-running, the task you are given is not otherwise particularly difficult outside of trying to manage the game's physics.    6/10EDIT: Having just finished the game (I was only a little way from it before), Dawn's character is very very subtly explained, in part. But the ending was abrupt and poorly done. Short game, nice story, good atmosphere, bad mechanics."
,Recommended,224460,13574612,"Posted: 24 December, 2014",all,World's Strongest Virgin,"Is this game worth your Time? That really depends what you're trying to get out of it.As a game I think Contrast falls flat. The controlls feel unnatural, the shadow thing feels like a gimmick, the puzzles are uninspired and the only challenge is rooted in the poor controls and a camera programmed solely to avoid the angles that you actually need. That said, the soundtrack is fantastic, the graphics, especially the character models, look like something from a Tim Burton stop motion (in a good way) and the story is compelling (that's not the same as good)In the end Contrast won me over. I feel the aesthetics win out over the gameplay shortcommings. Wait for this to go on sale and definitely shell out the extra couple bucks to get the collector's edition for the soundtrack."
