76561197995421497,Not Recommended,224460,32738539,Posted: 24 June,all,Steve-O,"5 Things You Should Know aboutContrastWhat's Is It?Contrast is an interesting concept piece.  A 1920s-ish (?) semi-noir story about a little girl and her imaginary friend, struggling to bring her estranged parents back together.  The plot is a mash-up of cliches that somehow add up to something original and the game play is unique and engaging.What's The Best Part?The gameplay really is unique.  Shifting from 3D to 2D and back again is fun, and the controls make this easy to do (although they are a bit loose otherwise - a ""walk"" button would've been nice.)What's The Worst Part?The game suffers from a lack of polish, which ultimately makes me say ""thumbs down."" The necessary elements are all there, but they all feel unfinished.  Like the devs got 90% of the way there and then just... stopped.  The controls.  The voices.  The puzzles.  Even the story gets 90% of the way to a conclusion and then stops just shy of actually explaining what's going on.  It could've really shined with a little more TLC.There are some games out there that give me a headache just from playing them.  I can't properly say WHY this happens, but it happens reliably when playing such games.  Contrast is one of those games.  Every time, after about ten minutes in-game, I have to go pop a few painkillers.Will I Like It?As much as I enjoyed playing this game, I was definitely ready for it to be over before I got to the end.  As creative and original as it is, it somehow gets old too quickly.  If you're the sort of person who likes to play unique games just to experience unique games, you may like this game despite its faults.Should I Buy It?The game is relatively short (I have 4.7 hrs on record and that represents one complete play-through.)  If you're curious, I'd say buy it, but wait until it's on sale.  If you're not sure, or you're the sort who expects to get somethingdefinitiveout of a game, it's safer to skip it.This has been a 5TYSK review. (#0001)"
