,Recommended,224460,30431123,Posted: 10 March,all,ExpertPlasma,"Contrast is an enjoyable puzzle platformer that has some unique mechanics, a great storyline but suffers from a few small gameplay issues.The shadow / light mechanics are unique and they work (most of the time) very well, making for some intriguing puzzles. The storyline is ambiguous but definitely interesting.The music and graphics are also fantastic, and better than I thought there'd be. I'd also recommend the soundtrack if you enjoy soundtracks.The game does have a minor annoyances when it comes to gameplay. Occassionally I found the controls a little clunky which made some more technical puzzle jumps hard. There were also a couple of glitches when trying to jump and shift into a wall.Overall those were only minor grievances and I easily lived with them. For its price, it's still great value for money.I recommend it if you want a nice but relatively quick puzzle platformer with some unique mechanics, a great storyline and fantastic music; just don't expect a 100% perfect gameplay experience."
,Recommended,224460,7736263,"Posted: 24 November, 2013",all,Cacau Birdmad,"When I saw Contrast at Steam Greenlight I knew that was a title I was going to play.Those who know me will easily understand why: Contrast has female protagonists, something I'm always looking forward to,  beautiful character and environment design, with an aesthetic close to my heart, an interesting mechanic and was non-violent, which is something I'm beginning to appreciate, even though I love to hack and slash things.So, as soon as it was available for pre-order, I decided to buy it, even if I was not at my best financially. It was worth it.First, the whole game was translated to brazilian portuguese, with the exception of the audio (which would've been really costly). Although I have no problem understanding english, this was a nice touch, specially when most people at my country don't have easy access to english lessons. Second, the game is beautiful, entertaining and interesting. I almost gasped at the final revelation: something I thought to be just an aesthetic choice, in the end, had much more meaning within the story.The puzzles were difficult enough to keep me interested, not hard to the point of making me want to give up nor easy to the point of leaving me bored. I once or twice thought of looking through a walkthrough, 'cause I'm lazy and always craving for more pieces of information surrounding a game's story, but I'd always close the window and decide to solve the puzzle myself. I loved when you activated some sort of ""memory"" and interacted with the shadows.There were glitches and bugs, like getting stuck between shadow-world and ""real-world"", but nothing really troubling.The controls were a bit weird at the beginning, I felt like Dawn walked too fast or something, but I got used to it quickly.  I could complain that the game is short. It is, really, but I honestly think it's worth it. It's an engaging experience and I think it lasts enough.  My only true complaint is that sometimes the cut-scenes would break the pace of the game. You'd walk a bit or solve one short puzzle and have a cut-scene right after it in a way that felt a tiny bit out of place. In the beginning of the game I felt there were too many short cut-scenes happening all the time.Still, it's not something that takes anything out of this wonderful game. This is a game you can show your non-gamer friends and family members too and I think would grab their attention. If you are open to it, you could ask them to help solving some puzzles, to make them engage more with the game.Visuals are lovely, gameplay is nice and the story is interesting.I'd recommend it for sure."
,Recommended,224460,10399013,"Posted: 8 June, 2014",all,Wulf,"Contrast is a game that grows on you and leaves you wanting more.The play style (Shadow shifting) for solving puzzles and progressing forward makes this game really fun.Although alot of elements were done before in various other titles, they were never done this good.The puzzles aren't too hard either so even the most novice players will get through them when stretching some brain muscles.The story slowly sucks you in from start to finish giving you just enough clues to keep you hanging on a threat but never enough to give it's story fully away.There were some clipping and frame rate issues here and there but was minor enough not to take up arms over it.I'd recommend this game to the young and old, hard-core puzzle fanatics or novices.Go on... give it a try... and enjoy.  :3"
