,Recommended,224460,15764661,"Posted: 9 May, 2015",all,TheDavisChanger,"Contrast is a great, non-violent 3D and 2D platformer.Much of the gameplay involves navigating the protaganist Dawn around a 3D 1920s city.  The boundaries of the city are warped in a twisted MC Escher way which is a far more stylish way of focusing the player in the playable space than invisible walls would be.  Dawn is led around this space by another character Didi to various areas where the player is to overcome various platforming puzzles to advance the story.The platforming is very clever.  Against most walls on which shadows are cast, Dawn can phase into the wall becoming a silhouette that can jump on the shadows cast by objects in 3D.  Prior to phasing in, Dawn can interact with objects to move the shadows into more traversable platforms.  She can also phase some 3D objects into the shadows with her to help solve puzzles and reach collectible items.  The 3D navigation is occasionally interrupted with a jittery camera and the player will occasionally pop out of shadows while phased without notice.  It seems the idea is to keep the camera perpendicluar to the wall while phased, but at bends or corners in the wall, this can get tricky.  Other than that, the controls are decent.The story is touching with a focus on family and the characters are unique, except for Dawn who is essentially a mute avatar.  Didi, the child who accompanies and directs Dawn, is adorable and determined to help her father Johnny.  Johnny is the reformed tramp that to whom the player immediately yields his sympathy.  Kat is at her wit's end with the unreliable Johnny as she raises Didi on her own.  Didi's--more so than Dawn's--resourcefulness and her comments--especially during the puppet show--highlight a theme of female empowerment without being heavy-handed in its delivery.I completed this game in four hours and would recommend it, especially at the going rate of a movie ticket.  The energetic Didi helps move the heartwarming story along in a stylish world with many ledges and crannies to explore.  Phasing from 3D into a 2D environment is a treat and the creatvity with which the 2D shadow puzzles were designed is impressive.  Despite camera and control issues in the 2D space, it would have been nice to explore this mechanic with more puzzles, but even so Contrast is a standout title."
,Recommended,224460,16745924,"Posted: 27 June, 2015",all,Stasis,"While ""Contrast"" is certainly not a ""AAA"" game - the gameplay is a little rough around the edges in ways that can put a hitch in some of the platforming puzzles, and the graphics look like they belong a generation earlier - it's filled with style and atmosphere that invokes Tim Burton, focused gameplay, and a feel that throws back to the earlier days of 3D platformers that kicked up a nice nostalgia trip.And it has some strong thematic similarities to Bioshock Infinite.Having clocked about 3 hours in it from start to finish, for what it is, the length feels just about right. This is a game you play for the overall experience, so it does what it wants to do without overstaying its welcome.Cool game."
