,Recommended,224460,12459552,"Posted: 11 October, 2014",all,worlebird,"I'm going to recommend this game, but I will give a caveat - I bought it on a good sale, when it was under 4 bucks.  At that price, it's well worth it.  At full price... probably not.This is a nice little game, with a really fantastic concept - the idea of shifting in and out of a 2D shadow world, and solving puzzles by moving objects and lights in 3D in order to properly align their shadows in 2D is very clever.  The music and atmosphere is quite nice as well, and the voice acting is well-done.  The story is a little thin, but I can't complain too much about that.Now, the down sides.  First off, the game is quite short.  I completed it in just a few hours, and I'm sure many players could do it in even less time.  Also, the controls are a little... I don't know how to describe it, exactly.  Often, when working in the 3D world, the camera will drift a little oddly, and you end up running into a wall unintentionally.  In the 2D world, you find yourself occasionally falling out of the shadows for small things - bumping into the wrong shadow, jumping across a wall of a darker color.  Not consistently, and not enough to ruin the game, but enough to make it a little frustrating occasionally.  Control just doesn't always feel right.While there are some good puzzles, and the atmosphere is quite interesting, often it feels like the designers weren't quite sure what to do with the concept.  Finally, gameplay is interrupted far too often by cutscenes.  I understand the desire to tell the story, and to set the stage for each new area, but it is annoying when control is taken from you every 5 minutes or so.This review ended up seeming a lot more negative than I actually feel about the game.  As I said at the start, if you get it on sale for less that 5 dollars or so, I think it's worth it, if you enjoy casual puzzle games with a unique atmosphere.  Ultimately, though, I would love to see this concept fleshed out more in another game.  It's a great idea that this game just couldn't quite do justice to."
,Recommended,224460,12455043,"Posted: 11 October, 2014",all,cuppscakes,"Contrast gets a hesitant thumbs up. It's a game that I'm dying to love, and while I completed it and did enjoy parts of it... it's hard to say I loved it. But it might be worth your time and money. Read on...On its surface, the game has a lot going for it: the art style is superb, the ""phase shift"" gimmick is really neat, and the storyline is decently interesting. The game, for a short experience, builds a nice little world and it does a solid job of make you invested in the characters. Also, the music is fantastic.However, a couple minor issues and one major issue gum up the experience. First, the game took me just over three hours (which included a few chunks of paused game) to complete, in its entirety. That means every achievement. I think I spend more time hunting down Easter eggs in Gone Home, frankly.Secondly, while the story segments are good, there's seemingly as much or more of them than gameplay. Especially early on, when the story is trying to establish itself, you walk ten feet and cutscene. Walk ten more, cutscene. Walk outside, another cutscene. I wanna play!Also, and this may just be me, but the ""phase shift"" gimmick was never used to its full potential. There are a few moments where you do something really cool, and everything falls in place, and it feels great. But those moments are more rare than they ought to be. Most of the puzzles or silly in their simplicity, which some of the tougher ones being more about fighting the way shadows work rather than being brain benders.And lastly, this is the big one. The controls... aren't great. If you're in shadow and run out of a space, you pop out. But it doesn't always work consistently. And collision detection is off at times. Also, I died a number of times when I didn't phase in like it was supposed to.At a couple of the later puzzles (the rotating wall in particular), I felt like I spent more time fighting the controls and shadow detection, as opposed to the puzzles. And felt myself pulled out of the story due to frustration.Now I know, that's a laundry list of problems. But most of them are because the premise and setting were so good... I wanted more. I wanted more puzzles, more areas to explore and more stuff to do. I got it on sale for just a couple bucks, and frankly am glad I'd waited. For a few bucks, it was a nice diversion over the weekend that left me ultimately satisfied.But for full price, for those easily frustrated or for those expecting a long, polished experience. Maybe watch a Let's Play and pass. So as stated above, I give this one a very cautious thumbs up, with a big ol' asterisk next to it."
