76561198009099194,Recommended,224460,17648402,"Posted: 21 August, 2015",all,Saber 5470,"This is a very tentative recommendation with some BIG caveats – if you are looking to buy this game, I would recommend getting it on sale, as I did, or borrowing off a friend. The reason for this is that the game feels very half-baked.Contrastis only a couple of hours long, ending before the game’s mechanics have really had a chance to flex their muscles. The story also seems to be truncated and cut down from what was originally intended. Further evidence of the game’s apparent rushed development is its controls and mechanics; the third-person camera controls feel very loose and wobbly, which is, to put it lightly, less than ideal for a game that features platforming as a central mechanic. Combine this with some inconsistent “shifting” controls and some poorly-designed puzzles and you are left with a game that often causes frustration where it should instead inspire satisfaction.So why am I still recommendingContrastin spite of these issues? In short, its central puzzle-platforming system is fascinating, one of the more creative mechanics I have seen in recent memory. As Dawn, the game’s silent protagonist, you have the ability to “shift” yourself and certain objects from the real, 3D world into the 2D world of shadows. This ability is the central focus of the game’s platforming puzzles, which may involve manipulating light sources and shadows to create platforming surfaces in more strategic puzzles, or using the shadows of moving objects to reach an objective in more fast-paced platforming action sequences. This interplay between the worlds of darkness and light forces you, the player, to see the world in a new way by placing shadows (things we often don’t even notice in games or otherwise) at the forefront of a scene. For this reason alone I would recommend this game, if only to game designers looking for interesting ideas.However, their is a second redeeming quality ofContrastand that is the game’s style. The game’s charming aesthetic and focus on playing as a young girl’s imaginary(?) friend can’t help but make you smile. Additionally, its 1920’s setting, a refreshing change to a period not often depicted in video games, provides us with a nice jazzy, big-band soundtrack. What little story there is features some quality voice acting and an intriguing sub-plot - it’s just a shame Compulsion didn’t have the time or resources to flesh the story out further.In summary,Contrastis a game that is full of potential but needed a few more months in the oven to be worth the $15-$20 asking price. However, if you’re looking for something that is short, charming, and original,Contrastmay very well be right up your alley."
