76561197998159333,Recommended,224460,11073146,"Posted: 4 July, 2014",all,Raveneer,"Contrast left me wanting more. I loved the shadow world you get to explore with Dawn and Didi. Its style and story is the kind of thing you best see in foreign films and the magic realism of Neil Gaiman (Mirrormask in particular kept cropping up as I played).Didi has a friend no one else can see named Dawn, who looks like she's an acrobat of some kind. What is her story? How did she gain her powers? Is she real or a figment of Didi's imagination? None of this is ever truly explained over the game's short running time (I finished it with all the achievements in a little over 3 hours), but what does happen is Dawn getting involved in the story of Didi and her parents. Her mom is a lounge singer and her father is a shiftless dreamer in debt to the mob. Jonny has one more scheme up his sleeve to get back in Didi's mom's good graces, and Didi will do everything in her power to help make it happen (with Dawn's help, naturally).It's hard not to get excited as you run and jump through Contrast's levels. The music and art design sell the world well, and the voice acting draws you into the struggles of its inhabitants, told enough enough as shadow plays. These are just for story design either; oftentimes you'll have to make use of the shadows you see to reach a switch or a puzzle piece. Collectibles take the form of either documents that reveal the game's backstory or glowing globes also used to power some of the game's puzzles.A lot has been said about the game's controls. I found them as tight as could be expected with the mechanics, with a handheld controller the best way to go. A keyboard and mouse setup could work but the best experience I think would be found with a controller if able.Contrast decides not to overstay its welcome, but I hope that the game devs do come back for an encore performance."
