,Recommended,224460,18002145,"Posted: 12 September, 2015",all,Zansonsha,"Few games marry platforing and puzzle elements as well as Contrast. Its shadow mechanic allows for a lot of unique solutions to puzzles, usually requiring the manipulation of the play field to set up platforms or move an object from one area to another. The solutions are fairly intuitive once you get the hang of it, and this keeps the pace of the game brisk. While the game is short (3 hours on my playthrough, with time included for exploration), it's exactly as long as it needs to be for the narrative it's telling.And oh boy, what a narrative. I admire the decision to tell a story of a troubled couple from their daughter's point of view, and to tell it in a highly Expressionist way. The noirish setting, the importance of casting light onto darkness and viewing events through projection and found documents leaves the player (and Didi) questioning the amount of agency they have in shaping the events occuring around them, but as the game progresses the player's actions do push the narrative forward, leaving one wondering if there's some reality-bending at play or if we're just in a land of childish wish fulfillment. The question is left to the player, as the narrative focuses less on making sense of the universe and more on the emotions of its central characters.But the experience isn't without a few drawbacks. While I personally found Didi to be a very compelling character, her constant direction can get tiring, as well as break the difficulty of some puzzles. Her guidance may be helpful for younger players or those inexperienced with 3D platformers, but a seasoned player may find themselves wishing for an option to forgo such a built-in hint system. Whether or not you identify with Didi can make or break the game because of this.The platforming is overall very tight and responsive, and the game grants abilities which ease progression later on. However, it has its moments of challenge which require timing so precise that getting it right may feel more like luck than skill. There is an excellent organic checkpoint system integrated into the mix, so failure is rarely punished and trial-and-error solutions are encouraged, so long as frustration doesn't set in too quickly.On a rare occasion, my character glitched into a wall or other fixture, but jumping/dashing out of them seems to fix the problem.Pros:Interesting, varied platforming and puzzle solving for a unique experience.Tight controls made for a gamepad.Beautiful and thought-provoking visual style.Largely well-acted characters with cheesy, but engaging dialogue.Positive portrayal of a female lead.Cons:Little replay value: collectables are included, but a completionist could grab them all in one playthrough.Difficulty is at parts too easy due to too much direction.Game length may affect one's opinion of its asking price.Overall, I found Contrast a fantastic experience, and certainly one that feels artistically-driven. The story and characters are compelling enough to push you forward without bogging the experience down with overlong cutscenes. Collecting all of the found documents in the game reveals an added light to the game's ending, encouraging exploration and abstract thinking, though the core of the game will be Didi's concerns for her father. If you're willing to forgive a young girl asking a lot of favors of you, the unique style and solid gameplay will make the experience worthwhile."
