76561197976576420,Recommended,224460,13696751,"Posted: 29 December, 2014",all,AKA Steve UK,"In Contrast you play as Dawn, who may, or may not, be the imaginary friend of a young girl called Didi. The game is set in a surreal fantasy city with strong tones of 1920’s Paris. Your role in the game is to accompany and guide Didi on her adventures around the city. The story takes place during a single night when Didi has snuck out, to try and reunite her mother and her estranged father.Contrast is a platform game with environment traversal puzzles. The game is fully 3D, but its unique feature is the ability to shift into the 2D world of shadows cast upon walls. Dawn uses the shadows to reach areas inaccessible in the 3D ‘real’ world.Contrast is a short game, I finished it in two sittings over the course of a weekend. Far from a criticism, the longevity was one of the aspects I appreciated most. It never outstayed its welcome or outlived its enjoyment. Unlike most games I finished it because I enjoyed it and wanted to see how it ended, rather than feeling obliged to grind on to the finish line hours after it ceased being fun.Contrast is also a fairly easy game. No 3D platform game is without a few tricky jumping sections and Contrast is no exception. But I never encountered anything that caused me to quit in frustration and I never felt lost in the game world or became stuck overlong on any particular puzzle. I never encountered any bugs, crashes, glitches or clipping errors during my play through.I enjoyed Contrast, particularly the art style and character design. I have a feeling that I would have enjoyed it less if it had been longer. But as it stands it was the perfect length for me. I would definitely recommend it to anyone looking for a fun and beautiful platform-game experience that doesn’t require a substantial investment of time."
76561198008550930,Recommended,224460,13713992,"Posted: 30 December, 2014",all,Waffle Sorter,"This is a fun game. Think Portal, if Portal were also Psychonauts.You play as Dawn, an acrobat with the ability to merge into her own shadow - and a curious inability to directly see or be seen by anyone other than Didi. This at first seems like simply an odd quirk, until the ending draws attention to it and refuses to actually offer explanation.The controls are good, if a little more responsive on the camera than I expected. The shadow-merging mechanic could use a little more polish - I often found myself popping out of the wall without being able to figure out why, and occasionally ended up across the room from where I had been a moment prior.The story is simple, which simply leaves more room to showcase the central mechanic and the world. Most characters (seen via projected shadows) talk with their hands a lot, presumably so you can tell who's talking as lips' shadows are very small."
,Recommended,224460,13715400,"Posted: 30 December, 2014",all,AaronThePugLord,"Contrast is like Bioshock Infinite, but a lot shorter.It revolves around that you as a player can fuse into shadows and move around in it, and by doing so clearing obstacles. You can mess around with objects and light sources to help you with the puzzles, and its a very interesting concept. But in some parts I feel the platforming in the shadows are a little bit clunky, and I have no idea why I would just jump out of the shadows sometimes without hitting any obstacles (well I assume i didnt hit anything).Music is great, voice acting is great, story can be better, controls are a bit awkward at times for both keyboard and controller,Good game overall, short but worth it. No brainer if its on discount."
