76561198173606567,Recommended,224460,32262956,Posted: 8 June,all,KeinSchiesse,"If you're looking for a platforming game with a chill environment and pace, this will suit you well. Its noir / pulp / theater / vaudeville setting will appeal to fans of those genres, as it has surreal environments with dark, moody European esque streets which the player traverses. I would recommend checking out actual gameplay videos, as I don't think the trailers here depict the game's pacing or more laidback atmosphere well.I like that the story is presented in somewhat obscure ways, in which you watch ""flashbacks"" from shadows cast upon the alleyways, to find out more about the father, his lover, and their daughter, as they struggle to make payments to unsavory characters. The platforming mechanic of warping into and out of shadow areas is novel at first, but its implementation can seem a bit strange at times too (i.e. figure out which picnic table umbrellas to open, to make a shadow casting a line for you to navigate on the 'shadow plane' that your character can warp into.., or later an at-times tedious elevator puzzle in which you push elevator buttons to change the cast shadows on the wall to be able to warp into the shadows and then progress upward, etc...)There are some platforming staples including collectibles, a dash ability to smash through previously unseen areas, etc...The daughter character can get a little annoying in a ""child character always scared / whining / crying"" type of way at times, but the voice acting in the game is well done overall.I think this game deserves more recognition than it ever got, as it is pretty relaxing to play and the stylized setting itself is pretty well done with a unique platforming mechanic, if you're a fan of old theater / noir type of environments and can look past the game's somewhat visible-graphical age, I think you may enjoy it."
